oid-views.description:
1. Configuration view. Only the OID mode is supported.
2. If this command and the views node are configured at the same time, first check whether the packet OID matches the OID of the current view. If yes, the rights are subject to this command. If not, the rights are subject to the views node.
3. The OID name is not unique. One name can correspond to multiple OIDs. If you want to exclude or contain an OID and the views node cannot be controlled, configure this node. For other scenarios, views node is recommended because the OID name is more explicit.

name.description: View name. The default view names AllView and DefaultView cannot be configured.

subtree-oid.description: View subtree. Only the OID can be configured.

type.description: Subtree type of the view. Options: Include and Exclude.

trap-source-profiles.description:
Application Scenario
1. This command needs to be configured only when it is necessary to specify a different source address for each NM or a different agent address for each NM SNMP v1 version trap. Otherwise, the global source address command (snmp-server trap-source) is used to configure the source address of trap or the agent address of SNMP v1 trap.

Precautions
1. When the NM IP address and vrf name exist in this table, the global source address command is ignored. If there are multiple policies with the same IP address and VRF name, the first policy is selected in ascending order.

2. If this command is used to associate an interface, if the interface fails to obtain the IPv4 or IPv6 address (the address type is the same as that of the NM), the source address is specified by the transmission protocol. The agent address in SNMP v1 trap is not specified.
3. When the NM address is of the IPv4 type, the agent address needs to be specified in SNMP v1 trap. When the NM address is IPv6, the agent address does not need to be specified.
4. A maximum of 2048 policies can be configured.

oid-views_schema.description:
1. Configuration view. Only the OID mode is supported.
2. If this command and the views node are configured at the same time, first check whether the packet OID matches the OID of the current view. If yes, the rights are subject to this command. If not, the rights are subject to the views node.
3. The OID name is not unique. One name can correspond to multiple OIDs. If you want to exclude or contain an OID and the views node cannot be controlled, configure this node. For other scenarios, views node is recommended because the OID name is more explicit.

name.description: View name. The default view names AllView and DefaultView cannot be configured.

subtree-oid.description: View subtree. Only the OID can be configured.

type.description: Subtree type of the view. Options: Include and Exclude.

trap-source-profiles_schema.description:
Application Scenario
1. This command needs to be configured only when it is necessary to specify a different source address for each NM or a different agent address for each NM SNMP v1 version trap. Otherwise, the global source address command (snmp-server trap-source) is used to configure the source address of trap or the agent address of SNMP v1 trap.

Precautions
1. When the NM IP address and vrf name exist in this table, the global source address command is ignored. If there are multiple policies with the same IP address and VRF name, the first policy is selected in ascending order.

2. If this command is used to associate an interface, if the interface fails to obtain the IPv4 or IPv6 address (the address type is the same as that of the NM), the source address is specified by the transmission protocol. The agent address in SNMP v1 trap is not specified.
3. When the NM address is of the IPv4 type, the agent address needs to be specified in SNMP v1 trap. When the NM address is IPv6, the agent address does not need to be specified.
4. A maximum of 2048 policies can be configured.
